---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Research" description="Ismail El Jamiy's PhD research on Handwritten Text Recognition of medieval Arabic scientific manuscripts and dedicated LLMs.">

  <article class="page-container">

    <header class="page-header">
      <h1 class="page-title">Research</h1>
      <div class="page-rule" aria-hidden="true"></div>
      <p class="page-subtitle">
        PhD in Artificial Intelligence · University of Toulouse (IRIT / IMT / CLLE) · 2025–2028
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="prose">

      <p class="drop-cap">
        The Arabic scientific tradition produced an extraordinary body of knowledge between
        the 8th and 15th centuries — treatises on algebra, optics, astronomy, and medicine
        that shaped European Renaissance thought. Thousands of these manuscripts survive in
        libraries across the Maghreb and the Middle East, largely undigitised and
        computationally inaccessible. My PhD aims to change that.
      </p>

      <h2>The Problem</h2>
      <p>
        Handwritten Text Recognition (HTR) has made remarkable progress on Latin scripts,
        but Arabic presents a distinct set of challenges:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Cursive connectivity</strong> — Arabic letters join within words in script-dependent ways, making segmentation non-trivial.</li>
        <li><strong>Contextual letterforms</strong> — Each character has up to four distinct shapes depending on its position in a word.</li>
        <li><strong>Historical variation</strong> — Medieval scribes used diverse regional hands (Maghribi, Mashriqi, Andalusian) with idiosyncratic ligatures and abbreviations.</li>
        <li><strong>Document degradation</strong> — Ink oxidation, water damage, worm holes, and palimpsest layering corrupt the visual signal.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Existing HTR systems trained on modern Arabic text fail on historical manuscripts,
        and even specialised historical HTR models rarely achieve the accuracy needed for
        downstream use in digital humanities research.
      </p>

      <h2>My Approach</h2>
      <p>
        My research pursues three complementary directions:
      </p>

      <div class="research-pillar">
        <div class="pillar-number">01</div>
        <div class="pillar-body">
          <h3>Robust HTR for historical Arabic</h3>
          <p>
            Training and fine-tuning deep neural architectures — including Vision-Language
            Models (VLMs) and Transformer-based sequence models — on curated corpora of
            digitised manuscripts. A key contribution is the construction of ground-truth
            datasets through collaboration with palaeographers and historians.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="research-pillar">
        <div class="pillar-number">02</div>
        <div class="pillar-body">
          <h3>Dedicated language models for medieval Arabic</h3>
          <p>
            Once text is recognised, the goal is to build LLMs pre-trained on medieval
            Arabic scientific prose. Standard Arabic LLMs are trained predominantly on
            modern text and struggle with archaic vocabulary, orthographic conventions,
            and domain-specific terminology. A dedicated model enables accurate translation,
            summarisation, and semantic search over manuscript corpora.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="research-pillar">
        <div class="pillar-number">03</div>
        <div class="pillar-body">
          <h3>End-to-end pipeline for digital humanities</h3>
          <p>
            The research aims to deliver not only models but a usable pipeline that
            historians can apply to new manuscripts: image pre-processing, HTR, correction
            assistance, and structured search. Accessibility and interpretability are
            first-class concerns.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2>Supervision</h2>
      <p>
        The PhD is conducted at IRIT (Institut de Recherche en Informatique de Toulouse),
        IMT (Institut de Mathématiques de Toulouse), and CLLE (Cognition, Langues, Langage,
        Ergonomie), under the University of Toulouse. This cross-disciplinary context
        brings together computer science, mathematics, and cognitive linguistics.
      </p>

      <h2>Why this matters</h2>
      <p>
        The manuscripts I study are not museum objects — they are primary sources for
        the history of science. Making them computationally accessible accelerates
        scholarship, enables cross-referencing at scale, and preserves endangered cultural
        heritage in digital form. It is technical research with a humanistic purpose.
      </p>

    </div>

  </article>

</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .page-container {
    max-width: 720px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 4rem 1.5rem 5rem;
  }

  .page-header {
    margin-bottom: 2.5rem;
  }

  .page-title {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: clamp(2rem, 4vw, 2.75rem);
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--fg);
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }

  .page-rule {
    height: 2px;
    background: linear-gradient(to right, var(--color-olive), transparent);
    border-radius: 1px;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  .page-subtitle {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    color: var(--fg-muted);
    margin: 0;
  }

  /* ── Prose ────────────────────────────────────────────────── */
  .prose {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: 1.125rem;
    line-height: 1.8;
    color: var(--fg);
  }

  .prose p { margin-bottom: 1.4em; }

  .prose h2 {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: 1.4rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-olive);
    margin: 2.5rem 0 0.75rem;
  }

  .prose h3 {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: 1.15rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--fg);
    margin: 0 0 0.5rem;
  }

  .prose ul {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin-bottom: 1.4em;
  }

  .prose ul li {
    padding-left: 1.25rem;
    position: relative;
    margin-bottom: 0.6em;
  }

  .prose ul li::before {
    content: "—";
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    color: var(--color-terracotta);
  }

  .drop-cap::first-letter {
    font-size: 4.5em;
    line-height: 0.78;
    float: left;
    margin-right: 0.08em;
    color: var(--color-terracotta);
    font-weight: 600;
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
  }

  /* ── Research pillars ─────────────────────────────────────── */
  .research-pillar {
    display: flex;
    gap: 1.5rem;
    margin: 1.75rem 0;
    padding: 1.5rem;
    border-left: 3px solid var(--color-olive);
    background: var(--bg-panel);
    border-radius: 0 0.375rem 0.375rem 0;
  }

  .pillar-number {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: 1.5rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-olive);
    opacity: 0.35;
    flex-shrink: 0;
    line-height: 1;
    padding-top: 0.1rem;
  }

  .pillar-body {
    flex: 1;
  }

  .pillar-body p {
    margin-bottom: 0;
    font-size: 1rem;
  }

  [data-theme="dark"] .prose h2,
  [data-theme="dark"] .pillar-number {
    color: var(--color-gold);
  }
</style>
